retrieval.tree_info:
Level-0 Motion: Too Many Kids Go To College, Side: for
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "College costs have exploded, creating a bubble with diminishing returns.", "argument": ["College costs have risen 300% after inflation since 1980, exceeding healthcare and housing cost increases.", "This creates a bubble characterized by runaway costs and unquestioning faith in its value, similar to tech and housing bubbles.", "There's no accountability for escalating tuition.", "College is turning into an expensive insurance policy against societal cracks.", "College is more a decades-long sentence of debt slavery."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Post-secondary education is linked with higher lifetime earnings and lower unemployment rates.", "argument": ["Studies show a conclusive link between post-secondary education and higher lifetime earnings.", "Studies show a conclusive link between post-secondary education and lower unemployment rates.", "The wage premium for college graduates, especially women, has been growing since the 1980s.", "Post-secondary education benefits society through increased productivity, reduced crime, and improved health and civic engagement.", "Even incomplete college attendance correlates with higher earnings.", "College provides exposure to diverse perspectives and builds social networks.", "College allows exploration of different fields and self-definition.", "Restricting access to this transformative period would be a grave mistake.", "Even incomplete college attendance correlates with higher earnings.", "College provides exposure to diverse perspectives and builds social networks.", "College allows exploration of different fields and self-definition.", "Restricting access to this transformative period would be a grave mistake.", "College increases opportunities.", "College increases earning potential.", "These benefits apply regardless of background."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "College is not a prerequisite for success.", "argument": ["In 1960, only 8% of American adults had degrees, yet success was widespread.", "Today, not having a degree renders you a second-class citizen, creating a caste system where elite college acceptance dictates future prosperity."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The cost argument against college ignores financial aid and diverse institutions.", "argument": ["Financial aid is widely available.", "There is a diversity of institutions, including affordable community colleges.", "Many colleges are more accessible than opponents claim."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The debate is about access to college, not quality or affordability.", "argument": ["The core issue is whether access to college should be restricted.", "Quality and affordability are separate, though related, concerns."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Student debt is high, and degree returns are diminishing.", "argument": ["Student debt exceeds a trillion dollars.", "The returns on a degree are diminishing.", "There is an oversupply of graduates in some fields (e.g., law, pre-med).", "Many graduates are working in unskilled jobs or are underemployed."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Post-secondary education is linked with higher lifetime earnings and lower unemployment rates.", "argument": ["Studies show a conclusive link between post-secondary education and higher lifetime earnings.", "Studies show a conclusive link between post-secondary education and lower unemployment rates.", "The wage premium for college graduates, especially women, has been growing since the 1980s.", "Post-secondary education benefits society through increased productivity, reduced crime, and improved health and civic engagement.", "Even incomplete college attendance correlates with higher earnings.", "College provides exposure to diverse perspectives and builds social networks.", "College allows exploration of different fields and self-definition.", "Restricting access to this transformative period would be a grave mistake.", "Even incomplete college attendance correlates with higher earnings.", "College provides exposure to diverse perspectives and builds social networks.", "College allows exploration of different fields and self-definition.", "Restricting access to this transformative period would be a grave mistake.", "College increases opportunities.", "College increases earning potential.", "These benefits apply regardless of background."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Low graduation rates are often tied to lack of resources, not just intelligence.", "argument": ["Low graduation rates are often tied to a lack of resources.", "We must invest in better pre-K-12 education, not limit access to higher learning.", "There are countless more high school dropouts holding low-level jobs than college graduates."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "College is not a solution for failing K-12 education.", "argument": ["Many college courses lack rigor, leaving graduates unable to write grammatically or think critically.", "Funneling more students into an expensive, often ineffective college system is not a solution for failing K-12 education.", "We need to reform K-12, not use college as a band-aid."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "College attendance, even incomplete, correlates with higher earnings and provides crucial experiences.", "argument": ["Even incomplete college attendance correlates with higher earnings.", "College provides exposure to diverse perspectives and builds social networks.", "College allows exploration of different fields and self-definition.", "Restricting access to this transformative period would be a grave mistake."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The debate is about access to college, not quality or affordability.", "argument": ["The core issue is whether access to college should be restricted.", "Quality and affordability are separate, though related, concerns."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "The current four-year BA system is often fraudulent, destructive, and obsolete.", "argument": ["The BA is fraudulent due to grade inflation and a focus on retention over rigor.", "The BA is destructive because it creates a false credential, devaluing those without it and pushing students into debt.", "The BA is obsolete because four years is often unnecessary, physical campuses are less relevant, and credentials are overemphasized compared to skills.", "A degree's value is 90% signaling and 10% actual learning.", "The current system conflates learning with credentialing.", "Social networking benefits primarily apply to elite institutions, further reinforcing the caste system."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Low graduation rates are often tied to lack of resources, not just intelligence.", "argument": ["Low graduation rates are often tied to a lack of resources.", "We must invest in better pre-K-12 education, not limit access to higher learning.", "There are countless more high school dropouts holding low-level jobs than college graduates."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "College equips students with valuable skills, and its positive effect has been demonstrated.", "argument": ["College equips students with valuable skills.", "Studies, including research on twins, isolate the impact of college itself and demonstrate its positive effect.", "Vocational alternatives are widely perceived as second best.", "College is more than vocational training; it's transformative.", "Surveys show increased life satisfaction post-college.", "College cultivates critical thinking and exposes students to new ideas.", "College fosters intellectual growth and personal development.", "College is more than vocational training; it's transformative.", "Surveys show increased life satisfaction post-college.", "College cultivates critical thinking and exposes students to new ideas.", "College fosters intellectual growth and personal development."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "College is a transformative experience that cultivates critical thinking and exposes students to new ideas.", "argument": ["College is more than vocational training; it's transformative.", "Surveys show increased life satisfaction post-college.", "College cultivates critical thinking and exposes students to new ideas.", "College fosters intellectual growth and personal development."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "College propels individuals forward, increasing opportunity and earning potential.", "argument": ["College increases opportunities.", "College increases earning potential.", "These benefits apply regardless of background."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Technology can revolutionize education delivery, making quality learning accessible to the masses.", "argument": ["Technology, such as immersive simulations and game-based learning, can revolutionize education.", "This can make quality learning accessible to more people."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "We need to shift the focus to skills and job creation, not just funneling students into college.", "argument": ["Education is not an absolute good; its value is conditional.", "The focus should be on creating good-paying jobs.", "Students should deliberately consider their futures instead of blindly pursuing degrees.", "The current system lacks accountability when education fails to provide returns.", "Finding a good plumber is harder than finding a lawyer.", "There is an artificial hierarchy that is fueled by the perceived necessity of a degree."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The claim that too many attend college is disproven by evidence.", "argument": ["In 2010, only 66% of 25-30 year olds had any college experience, which does not indicate an overwhelming influx.", "College encompasses a diverse range of institutions serving varied student populations, including older, working adults."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The US college attendance rate is high compared to other countries.", "argument": ["China and India have significantly lower college attendance rates (20% and 10%, respectively) compared to the US (40%).", "China and India's systems are brutally selective, focusing on a smaller, highly driven cohort."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The US economy increasingly demands post-secondary education.", "argument": ["Growth industries require post-secondary education.", "Retraining is crucial for future competitiveness due to the loss of industrial jobs.", "Individuals without a basic education, including a Bachelor\u2019s degree, will be left behind in the global economy.", "Broader access to higher education is essential for the American dream.", "Robotics and automation are eliminating low-skill jobs.", "The demand for educated workers is increasing.", "Restricting access to college creates a new class system.", "Opponents focus on a small percentage of skilled tradespeople.", "Robotics and automation are eliminating low-skill jobs.", "The demand for educated workers is increasing.", "Restricting access to college creates a new class system.", "Opponents focus on a small percentage of skilled tradespeople."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Increased educational attainment coincided with America's rise to global superpower status.", "argument": ["America's rise to global superpower status coincided with increased educational attainment.", "Critical thinking and innovation skills, honed in college, enable reinvention.", "China and India focus on higher education for economic development.", "Their students see degrees as pathways to success."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The future lies in a knowledge-based economy, increasing the demand for educated workers.", "argument": ["Robotics and automation are eliminating low-skill jobs.", "The demand for educated workers is increasing.", "Restricting access to college creates a new class system.", "Opponents focus on a small percentage of skilled tradespeople."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "College propels individuals forward, increasing opportunity and earning potential.", "argument": ["College increases opportunities.", "College increases earning potential.", "These benefits apply regardless of background."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Strengthening K-12 education is the solution, not restricting college access.", "argument": ["Restricting access is not the solution.", "Strengthening K-12 education is the right approach.", "Limiting college access is analogous to limiting high school access due to poor elementary preparation, which is undesirable."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Technology can revolutionize education delivery, making quality learning accessible to the masses.", "argument": ["Technology, such as immersive simulations and game-based learning, can revolutionize education.", "This can make quality learning accessible to more people."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Restricting college access is the wrong approach; we must invest in improving and expanding educational opportunities.", "argument": ["Restricting access is the wrong approach.", "Investment in improving and expanding educational opportunities is necessary.", "This will equip future generations to compete and thrive."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "The education system lacks accountability compared to other industries.", "argument": ["The education system is not held accountable like other industries.", "Unlike faulty products where refunds or lawsuits are possible, education leaves students trapped with debt.", "Bankruptcy law changes exacerbate the problem, making student loans inescapable."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Societal pressure to attend college should be resisted, and individuals should evaluate the cost-benefit ratio.", "argument": ["Individuals should think independently and question the necessity of a college degree.", "Evaluating the cost-benefit ratio of college is crucial.", "Critical evaluation can lead to a healthier education system by reducing the degree's status symbol and promoting genuine learning."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Education should focus on individual passions and mastery, not standardized degrees.", "argument": ["Education should focus on helping individuals discover and master their passions.", "This transforms education into a personalized experience, not a standardized four-year residential one.", "It breaks down the artificial barrier between college graduates and non-graduates."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Shifting from degrees to certifications can dismantle class stratification.", "argument": ["All career paths follow a similar progression of apprentice, journeyman, and master craftsman.", "Shifting from degrees to certifications can dismantle class stratification in America.", "This reinforces the idea that everyone is striving for mastery in their chosen fields."]}

